# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-graham-bell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] One of the more controversial figures to be included on the list was the occultist Aleister Crowley which Helen Haste saw as an example of British eccentricity.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] The poll and advocacy model of the final programme prevented the top ten figures from receiving critical scrutiny and the result was hagiographic.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] The Controller of BBC Two, Jane Root, said she hoped the list would produce "plenty of debate".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] However, the resulting television show left many controversies of its subjects unaddressed.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Two Irish nationals, Bono from U2 and Bob Geldof were included.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Sir Ernest Shackleton and Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington, were both Anglo-Irish in what is now the Republic of Ireland when all of Ireland was part of the United Kingdom, and Alexander Fleming in 20th place was Scottish.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] There are nine Scottish people on the list and thirteen of the 100 are women.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Only one entry was from the BAME community, (Freddie Mercury).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Four of the list are Welsh: Owain Glyndŵr, Aneurin Bevan, Richard Burton, David Lloyd George.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Two of the list are pre-English, (Boudica, King Arthur).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] The highest-ranked living person was Margaret Thatcher, placed 16th.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Ringo Starr was the only member of the Beatles not on the list.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Isambard Kingdom Brunel occupied the top spot in the polls for some time due largely to "students from Brunel University who have been campaigning vigorously for the engineer for weeks." However, a late surge in the final week of voting put Winston Churchill into first place.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] Although the BBC's original ranked list has been removed from their web server and what remains is only an alphabetical list of the Top 100, several other sources have preserved the original ranked list.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] There was some question as to whether the Richard Burton listed at No.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/100-greatest-britons] A BBC press release makes clear that the actor was intended.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] Calahan invented a stock ticker and formed the Gold and Stock Telegraph Company in 1867 to exploit the technology.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] Gold and Stock also developed a messenger system that sent instructions to and from the stock exchange floor.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] Three years later, the president of Gold and Stock Telegraph Company woke up to a burglar in his home, which inspired him to create a telegraph-based alert system.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] This system eventually connected 50 of his neighbors to a central station, where all the alert boxes were monitored.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] There were many small telegraph delivery companies in the United States in the 19th century.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In 1874, 57 district telegraph delivery companies affiliated and became **American District Telegraph** (ADT).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] With the increase in telephone usage in the late 19th century, ADT's messenger business slowly declined in popularity.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] ADT tried branching out and developing their signaling business while still maintaining their telegraph business as their primary income source.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] ADT incorporated into Western Union in 1901 and separated its messenger business from its main signaling business at that time.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In 1909, Western Union and ADT came under the control of American Telephone & Telegraph Company (AT&T).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] ADT began to expand into new areas, such as fire alarms and security alarms, between 1910 and 1930, but was kept separate from AT&T's Holmes alarm business.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] ADT became a publicly traded company in the 1960s.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In 1964, ADT was found to be a monopoly in restraint of trade.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] It was shown to provide almost 80% of the central station alarm service in the United States.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In some cities, such as New York City and Memphis, Tennessee, they were the sole provider.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] They were also found to have forced competitors out of business by lowering prices below cost.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] They would charge national accounts very low prices in cities with competitors and much higher prices where no competition was available.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] ADT was forced to adopt a national price list, which could not be varied, to help establish central station competitors in cities without competition and to pay fines and triple damages to the federal government, customers, and local competitors.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In early 1987, the firm Hawley Goodall, owned by Michael Ashcroft, bought the Indianapolis-based Crime Control Inc., the fourth-largest company in the U.S. security market, for $50 million.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] Later in the year, it bought ADT and moved to Bermuda.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] This purchase transformed Hawley into the leading security services business in the United States and resulted in the majority of its revenues coming from the North American market.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] As a result of the acquisition, Hawley changed its name to ADT Limited and decided to refocus its business around security services.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] At the end of 1987, the company sold its North American-based facility services business to Denmark's ISS A/S.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In 1997, ADT was purchased by Tyco International in a reverse takeover.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In January 2010, Tyco acquired Broadview Security (formerly Brink's Home Security), then ADT's largest competitor, for $2 billion.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] When the acquisition closed later that year, the Broadview name was discontinued, and Broadview's operations were integrated into ADT.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In September 2011, Tyco announced that it would split into three companies, ADT being one of the three.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] On October 1, 2012, ADT debuted as an independent public company and began trading on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE: ADT).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In 2014, it acquired the Canadian company Reliance Protectron Security Services from Reliance Home Comfort for a total of Can$555 million.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In February 2016, Apollo Global Management acquired ADT for nearly $7 billion and merged it with another home security firm, Protection 1.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] The purchase price represented a premium of approximately 56 percent over ADT's closing share price on February 12, 2016, and when combined with Protection 1, represented an aggregate transaction value of approximately $15 billion.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] The company went public again in January 2018 and again on the New York Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol ADT.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] As of 2023, Apollo still retains a majority share in ADT.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In April 2018, ADT acquired Aronson Security Group Inc. and Acme Security Systems as part of its commercial expansion plans.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In October 2019, Telus Corporation purchased all of ADT's Canadian assets for $700 million.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] By September 2020, Telus had renamed ADT's Canadian operations to Telus SmartHome Security.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In August 2020, Google announced that it would invest $450 million in ADT in exchange for a 6.6% equity stake.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] The partnership will leverage ADT's network of installers to sell and install Nest devices, and aim to integrate Google's AI and Nest smart home devices into ADT's services.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In November 2021, ADT announced an agreement to acquire Sunpro Solar, a residential rooftop solar power contractor, for $160 million in cash plus approximately 77.8 million shares of ADT common stock, implying a total enterprise value of approximately $825 million.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] The company was rebranded as "ADT Solar" and operates as a wholly owned subsidiary of ADT.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] On January 24, 2024, ADT announced that due to financial difficulties they will be closing their solar division.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] In September 2022, State Farm announced that it would invest $1.2 billion in ADT in exchange for a 15% equity stake, and that it would commit up to $300 million to an "opportunity fund" to support ADT's marketing, technology, and innovation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] At the same time, Google separately announced it would commit a further $150 million into a "success fund" for ADT.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] On July 10, 2023, ADT disclosed that errors were identified in regards to their non-cash goodwill impairment losses associated with their Solar reporting unit and related tax impacts.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] These errors were identified during the third quarter of 2022 and the first quarter of 2023.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] As a result, the company announced that their financial results for the third and fourth quarter of 2022 and the first quarter of 2023 would be restated.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] Consequently, investors were negatively impacted as ADT's stock price decreased during trading, the following day.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] ADT completed divesting its commercial security, fire and life safety business unit to private equity firm GTCR for $1.6 billion in October 2023.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/adt-security-services] As of March 2019, ADT had nine monitoring centers and a network of more than 17,000 professionals, serving 6 million customers in over 200 locations throughout the United States.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] The **Cygnet** (or **Aerodrome #5**) was an extremely unorthodox early Canadian aircraft, with a wall-like "wing" made up of 3,393 tetrahedral cells.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] It was a powered version of the Cygnet tetrahedral kite designed by Dr Alexander Graham Bell in 1907 and built by the newly founded Aerial Experiment Association.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] Bell's experiments with tetrahedral kites had explored the advantages of utilizing great banks of cells to create a lifting body leading to the Cygnet I.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] On 6 December 1907, Thomas Selfridge piloted the kite as it was towed into the air behind a motorboat, eventually reaching a height of 168 ft (51 m).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] This was the first recorded heavier-than-air flight in Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] While demonstrably able to fly as a person-carrying kite, it seemed unpromising as a direction for research into powered flight.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] It was difficult to control, and was in fact destroyed when it hit the water at the end of the flight.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] The following year, a smaller copy of the design was built as the **Cygnet II**, now equipped with wheeled undercarriage and a Curtiss V-8 engine.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] Attempts to fly the Cygnet II at Baddeck, Nova Scotia between 22 and 24 February 1909, met with failure.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] When the AEA Silver Dart was ready for flight testing, the engine was removed from the Cygnet II, and then returned.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] Rebuilt again as the **Cygnet III** with a more powerful 70 hp Gnome Gamma engine, its final flight was on 19 March 1912, at Bras d'Or Lake, Nova Scotia, piloted by John McCurdy.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] The results were highly unsatisfactory with the Cygnet III only able to lift off the ground for a foot or two, typically considered remaining in ground effect.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] After a final trial on 17 March, the tetrahedral cell bank failed structurally, leaving the aircraft irreparably damaged.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-cygnet] The Cygnet II and III were abandoned following this flight attempt.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The ***June Bug*** was an American "pioneer era" biplane built by the Aerial Experiment Association (A.E.A) in 1908 and flown by Glenn Hammond Curtiss.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The aircraft was the first American airplane to fly at least 1 km in front of a crowd.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] A *Scientific American* competition in 1907 offered a solid silver sculpted trophy, and $25,000 in cash, to be awarded to whoever made the first public flight of over 1 kilometer (3,280 ft) in an American aircraft.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] In 1907, Glenn Curtiss and the Aerial Experiment Association began building the *June Bug* with hopes of winning the Scientific American Cup.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The *June Bug,* also referred to as *Aerodrome #3* (the third powered airplane built by the A.E.A), included the previously used aileron steering system, but a shoulder yoke made it possible for the pilot to steer by leaning from side to side.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The aircraft featured a canard, horizontal surfaces, and a rear rudder.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The original varnish sealing the wing fabric cracked in the heat, so a mixture of turpentine, paraffin, and gasoline was used on the aircraft instead.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The *June Bug* had yellow wings due to the yellow ochre added to the wing mixture in order to make the aircraft show up better in the orthochromic-form monochrome photographs of the time.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The aircraft was named by Alexander Graham Bell after the common *Phyllophaga*, a beetle known colloquially in North America as the "June bug".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] This was because June bugs were observed to fly similarly to aircraft: they have large stiff outer wings for gliding, and more delicate smaller propeller-like wings that do the actual propulsion.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Curtiss in Hammondsport, New York, at Stony Brook Farm, on June 21, 1908.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Three of the four test flights were successful, with distances of 456 ft (139 m), 417 ft (127 m), and 1,266 ft (386 m), at an average speed of 34.5 mph (55.5 km/h).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] On June 25, performances of 2,175 ft (663 m) and 3,420 ft (1,040 m) were considered encouraging, and the A.E.A. contacted the Aero Club of America to sign up for the *Scientific American* Cup.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The Aero Club contacted the Wright brothers, offering them the chance to make an attempt first.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Orville wrote to decline the opportunity on June 30, as the Wrights were busy completing their deal with the United States government.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Orville's message was received by July 1, and G.H.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Curtiss took to the air as requested on July 4 (Independence Day).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The flight was made a public event, and spectators were allowed to watch.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The event was overseen by a delegation of 22 members of the Aero Club, headed by Alan R.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The Kalem Company's film crew covered the event, making the *June Bug* the first airplane in the United States to perform in a movie.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The nearby Pleasant Valley Wine Company opened its doors and offered free samples to the spectators at the event.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Manly, who had unsuccessfully tested the Langley Aerodrome in 1903, measured out the 1 km and 20 ft (6.1 m) distance with volunteer help.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] The *June Bug* took one false start, going 40 feet (12 m) high, but not far enough.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] On the second try, the airplane successfully flew 5,085 ft (1550 m) in 1 minute 42 seconds, winning the trophy and a US$25,000 cash prize.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Amidst the publicity following the flight, the Wrights sent a warning to Curtiss that they had not given permission for the use of "their" aircraft control system to be used "for exhibitions or in a commercial way".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] In fact, none of the A.E.A.'s aircraft used a wing-warping system like the Wrights' for control, relying instead on triangular ailerons designed by Alexander Graham Bell, which he successfully patented in December 1911.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] However, in 1913 a court ruled that this technique was an infringement of the Wright's 1906 patent.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Three years previous to the *June Bug*'s flight, the Wrights had made flights of up to 24 miles (38 km) without official witnesses.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] However, the Wrights would have been required to install wheels and dispense with a catapult launch to compete for the 1908 prize.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] From October to November, the *June Bug* was modified by adding floats to it in an attempt to create a seaplane.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Renamed ***Loon***, attempts to fly it began on Keuka Lake on November 28.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] Although the aircraft could achieve speeds of up to 29 mph (47 km/h) on the water, it could not take off, and on January 2, 1909, one of the floats filled with water, causing the *Loon* to sink.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] It was recovered, but rotted in a nearby boathouse.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-june-bug] A replica of the *June Bug* was built and flown in 1976 by Mercury Aircraft of Hammondsport.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] The **Red Wing** (or **Aerodrome #1**) was an early aircraft designed by Thomas Selfridge and built by the Aerial Experiment Association in 1908.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] It was named for the bright red color of its silk wings — chosen to achieve the best result with the photographic materials and techniques of the day.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] The aircraft was a pusher configuration with the engine and propellor behind the pilot.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] Lateral control was provided by the pilot shifting his weight from side to side.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] Baldwin piloted the aircraft off the frozen Keuka Lake near Hammondsport, New York in what would be the first public demonstration of a powered aircraft flight in the United States as well as the first flight by a Canadian pilot.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] The aircraft covered 319 ft (97 m) at a height of around 20 ft (6 m).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] This was said to be the longest "first flight" by either an aircraft or a pilot, up to that date.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] On March 17 Baldwin attempted a second flight, also from the ice of Keuka Lake, before crashing 20 seconds after takeoff.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-red-wing] A portion of the tail gave way, bringing the test to an end.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The ***Silver Dart*** (or ***Aerodrome #4***) was a derivative of an early aircraft built by a Canadian/U.S. team, which after many successful flights in Hammondsport, New York, earlier in 1908, was dismantled and shipped to Baddeck, Nova Scotia.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] It was flown from the ice of Baddeck Bay, a sub-basin of Bras d'Or Lake, on 23 February 1909, making it the first controlled powered flight in Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The aircraft was piloted by one of its designers, Douglas McCurdy.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The original *Silver Dart* was designed and built by the Aerial Experiment Association (AEA), which had been formed under the guidance of Dr.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] From 1891, Bell had begun experiments at Baddeck and Hammondsport to develop motor-powered heavier-than-air aircraft.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] By 1908, the success of the AEA was seen in a series of ground-breaking designs, culminating in the *Silver Dart*.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] By the time the *Silver Dart* was constructed in late 1908, it was the Aerial Experiment Association's fourth flying machine.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] One of its precursors, the *June Bug*, had already broken records.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] It won the *Scientific American* Trophy for making the first official one mile (1609 m) flight in North America.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The frame and structure of the *Silver Dart* were made of steel tube, bamboo, friction tape, wire and wood.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The wings were covered with rubberized, silvery balloon cloth provided by Capt.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Thomas Scott Baldwin of Hammondsport; hence the name the "Silver Dart".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Its Kirkham engine, supplied by Glenn Curtiss, was a reliable V-8 that developed 50 horsepower (37 kW) at 1,000 RPM.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The propeller was carved from a solid block of wood.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The aircraft had what is now called a canard or an "elevator in front" design.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Like most aircraft of its day the *Silver Dart* had poor control characteristics; likewise, it had no brakes.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] When the *Silver Dart* lifted off on 23 February 1909, it flew only half a mile (800 m) at an elevation from three to nine meters, and a speed of roughly 65 kilometres per hour (40 mph).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The aircraft was the first powered, heavier-than-air machine to fly in Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Other records were soon to fall; on 10 March 1909, the *Silver Dart* flown again by McCurdy completed a circular course over a distance of more than 35 kilometres (22 mi).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The first passenger flight in Canada was made in the *Silver Dart* on 2 August 1909.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The Canadian Army was unimpressed at the headway made by the group.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The general impression of the time was that aircraft would never amount to much in actual warfare.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Despite official scepticism, the Association was finally invited to the military base at Camp Petawawa to demonstrate the aircraft.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The sandy terrain made a poor runway for an aircraft with landing wheels about 2 inches (50 mm) wide.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The *Silver Dart* had great difficulty taking off.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] On its fifth flight on 2 August 1909, McCurdy wrecked the craft when one wheel struck a rise in the ground while landing.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Although a significant aircraft in Canada, the location of the initial design and construction of the *Silver Dart* made it an American design.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Following the disbanding of the AEA, founding members, McCurdy and F.W.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] ("Casey") Baldwin obtained the Canadian patent rights for Aerodrome No.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] 4 (*The Silver Dart*), for the express purpose of producing a Canadian-made version.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] 2* were built by the Canadian Aerodrome Company, the newly formed company that Baldwin and McCurdy established in 1909.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] There is a reconstruction of the *Silver Dart* on display at the Canada Aviation and Space Museum in Ottawa.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The reconstruction was built by volunteers from the Royal Canadian Air Force between 1956 and 1958 to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the first flight.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The aircraft flew over Baddeck Bay on the day of the anniversary but crashed due to high winds.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] A number of other scaled and full-scale replicas are found in Canadian and museum collections in other parts of the world, including examples at the Canadian Bushplane Heritage Centre in Sault Ste.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Marie, the Atlantic Canada Aviation Museum, Reynolds-Alberta Museum, Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum The Canadian Aviation Museum in Windsor On.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] A.G.Bell Museum, Baddeck Nova Scotia, the National Air Force Museum of Canada and Aero Space Museum of Calgary.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] A small group of volunteers from the not-for-profit Aerial Experiment Association 2005 Inc. completed building a flying replica of the *Silver Dart* in early 2009.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The main goal of the group was to recreate the original flight on 23 February 2009 – again on the frozen surface of Baddeck Bay near Baddeck, Nova Scotia.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] However, due to weather conditions forecast for the 23rd, the centennial flight and fly-by occurred on 22 February.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] After a temporary repair made to the front wheel, former Canadian astronaut Bjarni Tryggvason piloted five successful flights that day.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The replica is officially considered a Canadian heritage project, and throughout the year was the centerpiece of a series of events celebrating the centennial of the *Silver Dart's* first flight in Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] In 2013, it was moved to the Alexander Graham Bell Museum in Baddeck, where it will be on permanent display.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Numerous other activities took place in 2009 to celebrate the Centennial of Flight, including a new exhibition entitled "Canadian Wings – A Remarkable Century of Flight" at the Canada Aviation Museum in Ottawa and a trans-Canada flight of vintage aircraft.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The no longer functional official Nova Scotia Ministry of Tourism website *Centennial Celebration of the Flight of the Silver Dart in Baddeck* promoted the flight and anniversary activities in Baddeck throughout the centennial.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Various historical photos and documents were posted on that site, in a virtual museum presentation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] The 824 Silver Dart Squadron of the Royal Canadian Air Cadets in St.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Peter's, Nova Scotia is named in honour of the *Silver Dart*.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Another cadet squadron, the 602 McCurdy Squadron of the Royal Canadian Air Cadets – in Florence, Nova Scotia – is named in honour of John McCurdy, the original pilot of the *Silver Dart*.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Physical commemorations include **Silver Dart Drive**, located in Mississauga, Ontario, which is a perimeter roadway within the confines of Toronto Pearson International Airport.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] Another Ontario commemorative site is the double ice-surface arena in CFB Petawawa, known as the *Silver Dart Arena*.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] On the 50th anniversary of its first flight, Canada Post issued a Canadian *Silver Dart* stamp on 23 February 1959.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/aea-silver-dart] During the Canadian Centenary of Flight, Canada Post honoured the *Silver Dart* – and the first flight in Canada – with a Canadian postage stamp released on 23 February 2009.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father, grandfather, and brother had all been associated with work on elocution and speech, and both his mother and wife were deaf, profoundly influencing Bell's life's work.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His research on hearing and speech further led him to experiment with hearing devices, which eventually culminated in his being awarded the first U.S. patent for the telephone, on March 7, 1876.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell considered his invention an intrusion on his real work as a scientist and refused to have a telephone in his study.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Many other inventions marked Bell's later life, including ground-breaking work in optical telecommunications, hydrofoils, and aeronautics.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell also had a strong influence on the National Geographic Society and its magazine while serving as its second president from 1898 to 1903.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For *National Geographic*, Bell wrote under the pseudonym **H.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Beyond his work in engineering, Bell had a deep interest in the emerging science of heredity.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His work in this area has been called "the soundest, and most useful study of human heredity proposed in nineteenth-century America ...
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was born in Edinburgh, Scotland, on March 3, 1847, to Alexander Melville Bell, a phonetician, and Eliza Grace Bell (née Symonds).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The family home was on South Charlotte Street in Edinburgh, where a stone inscription marks it as Bell's birthplace.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He had two brothers: Melville James Bell (1845–1870) and Edward Charles Bell (1848–1867), who both died of tuberculosis.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 10, however, he made a plea to his father to have a middle name like his two brothers.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For his 11th birthday, his father acquiesced and allowed him to adopt the name "Graham", chosen out of respect for Alexander Graham, a Canadian being treated by his father who was also a family friend.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] To close relatives and friends he remained "Aleck".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his siblings attended a Presbyterian Church in their youth.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As a child, Bell displayed a curiosity about his world; he gathered botanical specimens and ran experiments at an early age.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His best friend was Ben Herdman, a neighbour whose family operated a flour mill.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At the age of 12, Bell built a homemade device that combined rotating paddles with sets of nail brushes, creating a simple dehusking machine that was put into operation at the mill and used steadily for a number of years.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In return, Ben's father John Herdman gave both boys the run of a small workshop in which to "invent".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] From his early years, Bell showed a sensitive nature and a talent for art, poetry, and music that his mother encouraged.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With no formal training, he mastered the piano and became the family's pianist.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Though normally quiet and introspective, he revelled in mimicry and "voice tricks" akin to ventriloquism that entertained family guests.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was also deeply affected by his mother's gradual deafness (she began to lose her hearing when he was 12), and learned a manual finger language so he could sit at her side and tap out silently the conversations swirling around the family parlour.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also developed a technique of speaking in clear, modulated tones directly into his mother's forehead, whereby she would hear him with reasonable clarity.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's preoccupation with his mother's deafness led him to study acoustics.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His family was long associated with the teaching of elocution: his grandfather, Alexander Bell, in London, his uncle in Dublin, and his father, in Edinburgh, were all elocutionists.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father published a variety of works on the subject, several of which are still well known, especially *The Standard Elocutionist* (1860), which appeared in Edinburgh in 1868.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] *The Standard Elocutionist* appeared in 168 British editions and sold over 250,000 copies in the United States alone.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It explains methods to instruct deaf-mutes (as they were then known) to articulate words and read other people's lip movements to decipher meaning.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father taught him and his brothers not only to write Visible Speech but to identify any symbol and its accompanying sound.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell became so proficient that he became a part of his father's public demonstrations and astounded audiences with his abilities.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He could decipher Visible Speech representing virtually every language, including Latin, Scottish Gaelic, and even Sanskrit, accurately reciting written tracts without any prior knowledge of their pronunciation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As a young child, Bell, like his brothers, was schooled at home by his father.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At an early age, he was enrolled at the Royal High School in Edinburgh.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But he left at age 15, having completed only the first four forms.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His school record was undistinguished, marked by absenteeism and lacklustre grades.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His main interest remained in the sciences, especially biology, while he treated other school subjects with indifference, to his father's dismay.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon leaving school, Bell travelled to London to live with his grandfather, Alexander Bell, on Harrington Square.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During the year he spent with his grandfather, a love of learning was born, with long hours spent in serious discussion and study.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The elder Bell took great efforts to have his young pupil learn to speak clearly and with conviction, attributes he would need to become a teacher himself.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 16, Bell secured a position as a "pupil-teacher" of elocution and music at Weston House Academy in Elgin, Moray, Scotland.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although enrolled as a student in Latin and Greek, he instructed classes himself in return for board and £10 per session.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The next year, he attended the University of Edinburgh, joining his brother Melville, who had enrolled there the previous year.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1868, Bell completed his matriculation exams and was accepted for admission to University College London, though he did not complete his studies, as his family emigrated to Canada in 1870 following the deaths of his brothers Edward and Melville from tuberculosis.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father encouraged his interest in speech and, in 1863, took his sons to see a unique automaton developed by Sir Charles Wheatstone based on the earlier work of Baron Wolfgang von Kempelen.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The rudimentary "mechanical man" simulated a human voice.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was fascinated by the machine, and after he obtained a copy of von Kempelen's book, published in German, and had laboriously translated it, he and Melville built their own automaton head.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Their father, highly interested in their project, offered to pay for any supplies and spurred the boys on with the enticement of a "big prize" if they were successful.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While his brother constructed the throat and larynx, Bell tackled the more difficult task of recreating a realistic skull.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His efforts resulted in a remarkably lifelike head that could "speak", albeit only a few words.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The boys would carefully adjust the "lips" and when a bellows forced air through the windpipe, a very recognizable *Mama* ensued, to the delight of neighbours who came to see the invention.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Intrigued by the results of the automaton, Bell continued to experiment with a live subject, the family's Skye Terrier, Trouve.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After he taught it to growl continuously, Bell would reach into its mouth and manipulate the dog's lips and vocal cords to produce a crude-sounding "Ow ah oo ga ma ma".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With little convincing, visitors believed his dog could articulate "How are you, grandmama?" Indicative of his playful nature, his experiments convinced onlookers that they saw a "talking dog".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These initial forays into experimentation with sound led Bell to undertake his first serious work on the transmission of sound, using tuning forks to explore resonance.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 19, Bell wrote a report on his work and sent it to philologist Alexander Ellis, a colleague of his father.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Ellis immediately wrote back indicating that the experiments were similar to existing work in Germany, and also lent Bell a copy of Hermann von Helmholtz's work, *The Sensations of Tone as a Physiological Basis for the Theory of Music*.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Dismayed to find that groundbreaking work had already been undertaken by Helmholtz, who had conveyed vowel sounds by means of a similar tuning fork "contraption", Bell pored over the book.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1865, when the Bell family moved to London, Bell returned to Weston House as an assistant master and, in his spare hours, continued experiments on sound using a minimum of laboratory equipment.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell concentrated on experimenting with electricity to convey sound and later installed a telegraph wire from his room in Somerset College to that of a friend.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Throughout late 1867, his health faltered mainly through exhaustion.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His brother Edward was similarly affected by tuberculosis.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While Bell recovered (by then referring to himself in correspondence as "A.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell") and served the next year as an instructor at Somerset College, Bath, England, his brother's condition deteriorated.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon his brother's death, Bell returned home in 1867.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With aspirations to obtain a degree at University College London, Bell considered his next years preparation for the degree examinations, devoting his spare time to studying.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Helping his father in Visible Speech demonstrations and lectures brought Bell to Susanna E.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Hull's private school for the deaf in South Kensington, London.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His first two pupils were deaf-mute girls who made remarkable progress under his tutelage.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While Melville seemed to achieve success on many fronts, including opening his own elocution school, applying for a patent on an invention, and starting a family, Bell continued as a teacher.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In May 1870, Melville died from complications of tuberculosis, causing a family crisis.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father had also experienced a debilitating illness earlier in life and been restored to health by convalescence in Newfoundland.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's parents embarked upon a long-planned move when they realized that their remaining son was also sickly.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Acting decisively, Alexander Melville Bell asked Bell to arrange for the sale of all the family property, conclude all his brother's affairs (Bell took on his last student, curing a pronounced lisp), and join his father and mother in setting out for Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Reluctantly, Bell also had to conclude a relationship with Marie Eccleston, who, as he had surmised, was not prepared to leave England with him.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1870, 23-year-old Bell travelled with his parents and his brother's widow, Caroline Margaret Ottaway, to Paris, Ontario, to stay with Thomas Henderson, a Baptist minister and family friend.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bells soon purchased a farm of 10.5 acres (4.2 ha) at Tutelo Heights (now called Tutela Heights), near Brantford, Ontario.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The property consisted of an orchard, large farmhouse, stable, pigsty, hen-house, and a carriage house, which bordered the Grand River.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At the homestead, Bell set up a workshop in the converted carriage house near what he called his "dreaming place", a large hollow nestled in trees at the back of the property above the river.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Despite his frail condition upon arriving in Canada, Bell found the climate and environs to his liking and rapidly improved.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He continued his interest in the study of the human voice, and when he discovered the Six Nations Reserve across the river at Onondaga, learned the Mohawk language and translated its unwritten vocabulary into Visible Speech symbols.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For his work, Bell was awarded the title of Honorary Chief and participated in a ceremony where he donned a Mohawk headdress and danced traditional dances.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After setting up his workshop, Bell continued experiments based on Helmholtz's work with electricity and sound.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also modified a melodeon (a type of pump organ) to transmit its music electrically over a distance.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Once the family was settled, Bell and his father made plans to establish a teaching practice and in 1871, he accompanied his father to Montreal, where Melville was offered a position to teach his System of Visible Speech.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father was invited by Sarah Fuller, principal of the Boston School for Deaf Mutes (later to become the public Horace Mann School for the Deaf) to introduce the Visible Speech System by providing training for Fuller's instructors, but he declined the post in favour of his son.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Travelling to Boston in April 1871, Bell proved successful in training the school's instructors.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He was asked to repeat the programme at the American Asylum for Deaf-mutes in Hartford, Connecticut, and the Clarke School for the Deaf in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning home to Brantford after six months abroad, Bell continued his experiments with his "harmonic telegraph".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The basic concept behind his device was that messages could be sent through a single wire if each was transmitted at a different pitch, but work on both the transmitter and receiver was needed.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Unsure of his future, he contemplated returning to London to complete his studies, but decided to return to Boston as a teacher.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father helped him set up his private practice by contacting Gardiner Greene Hubbard, the president of the Clarke School for the Deaf for a recommendation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Teaching his father's system, in October 1872, Alexander Bell opened his "School of Vocal Physiology and Mechanics of Speech" in Boston, which attracted a large number of deaf pupils, with his first class numbering 30 students.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While he was working as a private tutor, one of his pupils was Helen Keller, who came to him as a young child unable to see, hear, or speak.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] She later said that Bell dedicated his life to the penetration of that "inhuman silence which separates and estranges".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1893, Keller performed the sod-breaking ceremony for the construction of Bell's new Volta Bureau, dedicated to "the increase and diffusion of knowledge relating to the deaf".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1891, Bell established the American Association for the Promotion of the Teaching of Speech to the Deaf (AAPTSD) in New York and endowed the organization with a gift of $25,000.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While endorsing the teaching of speech to the deaf, Bell remained neutral as to whether oral, manual or a combination of the three methods would best benefit the student.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Throughout his life, Bell sought to assimilate the deaf and hard of hearing with the broader population.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He encouraged speech therapy and lip-reading as well as sign language.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He outlined this in an 1898 paper detailing his belief that, with resources and effort, the deaf could be taught to read lips and speak (known as oralism), enabling their integration with wider society.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Members of the Deaf community have criticized Bell for supporting lip-reading over the use of sign language.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1872, Bell became professor of Vocal Physiology and Elocution at the Boston University School of Oratory.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During this period, he alternated between Boston and Brantford, spending summers in his Canadian home.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At Boston University, Bell was "swept up" by the excitement engendered by the many scientists and inventors living in the city.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He continued his research in sound and endeavoured to find a way to transmit musical notes and articulate speech, but although absorbed by his experiments, he found it difficult to devote enough time to experimentation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With days and evenings occupied by his teaching and private classes, Bell began to stay awake late into the night, running experiment after experiment in rented facilities at his boarding house.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Keeping "night owl" hours, he worried that his work would be discovered and took great pains to lock up his notebooks and laboratory equipment.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell had a specially made table where he could place his notes and equipment inside a locking cover.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His health deteriorated as he had severe headaches.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning to Boston in autumn 1873, Bell made a far-reaching decision to concentrate on his experiments in sound.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Giving up his lucrative private Boston practice, Bell retained only two students, six-year-old "Georgie" Sanders, deaf from birth, and 15-year-old Mabel Hubbard.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Each played an important role in the next developments.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Georgie's father, Thomas Sanders, a wealthy businessman, offered Bell a place to stay in nearby Salem with Georgie's grandmother, complete with a room to "experiment".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the offer was made by Georgie's mother and followed the year-long arrangement in 1872 where her son and his nurse had moved to quarters next to Bell's boarding house, it was clear that Mr.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The arrangement was for teacher and student to continue their work together, with free room and board thrown in.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Mabel was a bright, attractive girl ten years Bell's junior who became the object of his affection.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Having lost her hearing after a near-fatal bout of scarlet fever close to her fifth birthday, she had learned to read lips but her father, Gardiner Greene Hubbard, Bell's benefactor and personal friend, wanted her to work directly with her teacher.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1874, Bell's initial work on the harmonic telegraph had entered a formative stage, with progress made both at his new Boston "laboratory" (a rented facility) and at his family home in Canada a big success.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While working that summer in Brantford, Bell experimented with a "phonautograph", a pen-like machine that could draw shapes of sound waves on smoked glass by tracing their vibrations.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell thought it might be possible to generate undulating electrical currents that would correspond to sound waves.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also believed that he would be able to convert the undulating currents back into sound by tuning multiple metal reeds to different frequencies.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But he had no working model to demonstrate the feasibility of these ideas.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1874, telegraph message traffic was rapidly expanding and, in the words of Western Union President William Orton, had become "the nervous system of commerce".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Orton had contracted with inventors Thomas Edison and Elisha Gray to find a way to send multiple telegraph messages on each telegraph line to avoid the great cost of constructing new lines.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell mentioned to Gardiner Hubbard and Thomas Sanders that he was working on a method of sending multiple tones on a telegraph wire using a multi-reed device, the two began to financially support Bell's experiments.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent matters were handled by Hubbard's patent attorney, Anthony Pollok.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In March 1875, Bell and Pollok visited the scientist Joseph Henry, then the director of the Smithsonian Institution, to ask his advice on the electrical multi-reed apparatus that Bell hoped would transmit the human voice by telegraph.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Henry said Bell had "the germ of a great invention".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell said that he lacked the necessary knowledge, Henry replied, "Get it!" That declaration greatly encouraged Bell to keep trying, even though he had neither the equipment needed to continue his experiments nor the ability to create a working model of his ideas.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But a chance meeting in 1874 between Bell and Thomas A.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson, an experienced electrical designer and mechanic at the electrical machine shop of Charles Williams, changed that.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With financial support from Sanders and Hubbard, Bell hired Watson as his assistant, and the two experimented with acoustic telegraphy.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On June 2, 1875, Watson accidentally plucked one of the reeds and Bell, at the receiving end of the wire, heard the reed's overtones that would be necessary for transmitting speech.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That demonstrated to Bell that only one reed or armature was necessary, not multiple reeds.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This led to the "gallows" sound-powered telephone, which could transmit indistinct, voice-like sounds, but not clear speech.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1875, Bell developed an acoustic telegraph and drew up a patent application for it.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meanwhile, Elisha Gray was also experimenting with acoustic telegraphy and thought of a way to transmit speech using a water transmitter.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On February 14, 1876, Gray filed a caveat with the U.S.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent Office for a telephone design that used a water transmitter.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That same morning, Bell's lawyer filed Bell's application with the patent office.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] There is considerable debate about who arrived first and Gray later challenged the primacy of Bell's patent.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was in Boston on February 14 and did not arrive in Washington until February 26.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent Office issued Bell patent 174,465.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 10, Bell succeeded in getting his telephone to work, using a liquid transmitter similar to Gray's design.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Vibration of the diaphragm caused a needle to vibrate in the water, varying the electrical resistance in the circuit.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson—Come here—I want to see you" into the liquid transmitter, Watson, listening at the receiving end in an adjoining room, heard the words clearly.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After March 1876, Bell focused on improving the electromagnetic telephone and never used Gray's liquid transmitter in public demonstrations or commercial use.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The examiner raised the question of priority for the variable resistance feature of the telephone before approving Bell's patent application.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He told Bell that his claim for the variable resistance feature was also described in Gray's caveat.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell pointed to a variable resistance device in his previous application in which he described a cup of mercury, not water.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He had filed the mercury application at the patent office on February 25, 1875, long before Gray described the water device.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In addition, Gray abandoned his caveat, and because he did not contest Bell's priority, the examiner approved Bell's patent on March 3, 1876.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Gray had reinvented the variable resistance telephone, but Bell was the first to write down the idea and test it in a telephone.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The patent examiner, Zenas Fisk Wilber, later stated in an affidavit that he was an alcoholic who was much in debt to Bell's lawyer, Marcellus Bailey, with whom he had served in the Civil War.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He said he had shown Bailey Gray's patent caveat.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Wilber also said (after Bell arrived in Washington D.C. from Boston) that he showed Bell Gray's caveat and that Bell paid him $100 (equivalent to $2,900 in 2025).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell said they discussed the patent only in general terms, although in a letter to Gray, Bell admitted that he learned some of the technical details.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell denied in an affidavit that he ever gave Wilber any money.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 10, 1876, Bell used "the instrument" in Boston to call Thomas Watson who was in another room but out of earshot.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson, come here – I want to see you" and Watson soon appeared at his side.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Continuing his experiments in Brantford, Bell brought home a working model of his telephone.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On August 3, 1876, from the telegraph office in Brantford, Bell sent a telegram to the village of Mount Pleasant four miles (six kilometres) away, indicating that he was ready.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He made a telephone call via telegraph wires and faint voices were heard replying.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The following night, he amazed guests as well as his family with a call between the Bell Homestead and the office of the Dominion Telegraph Company in Brantford along an improvised wire strung up along telegraph lines and fences, and laid through a tunnel.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This time, guests at the household distinctly heard people in Brantford reading and singing.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The third test, on August 10, 1876, was made via the telegraph line between Brantford and Paris, Ontario, eight miles (thirteen kilometres) away.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This test is said by many sources to be the "world's first long-distance call".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It proved that the telephone could work over long distances, at least as a one-way call.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The first two-way (reciprocal) conversation over a line occurred between Cambridge and Boston (roughly 2.5 miles) on October 9, 1876.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During that conversation, Bell was on Kilby Street in Boston and Watson was at the offices of the Walworth Manufacturing Company.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his partners, Hubbard and Sanders, offered to sell the patent outright to Western Union for $100,000, equal to $3,023,438 today, but it did not work (according to an apocryphal story, the president of Western Union balked, countering that the telephone was nothing but a toy).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Two years later, he told colleagues that if he could get the patent for $25 million (equal to $834,051,724 today), he would consider it a bargain.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By then, the Bell company no longer wanted to sell the patent.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's investors became millionaires while he fared well from residuals and at one point had assets of nearly $1 million.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell began a series of public demonstrations and lectures to introduce the new invention to the scientific community as well as the general public.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] A short time later, his demonstration of an early telephone prototype at the 1876 Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia brought the telephone to international attention.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Influential visitors to the exhibition included Emperor Pedro II of Brazil.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the judges at the Exhibition, Sir William Thomson (later Lord Kelvin), a renowned Scottish scientist, described the telephone as "the greatest by far of all the marvels of the electric telegraph".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On January 14, 1878, at Osborne House, on the Isle of Wight, Bell demonstrated the device to Queen Victoria, placing calls to Cowes, Southampton, and London.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These were the first publicly witnessed long-distance telephone calls in the UK.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The queen found the process "quite extraordinary" although the sound was "rather faint".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] She later asked to buy the equipment that was used, but Bell offered to make "a set of telephones" specifically for her.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell Telephone Company was created in 1877, and by 1886, more than 150,000 people in the U.S. owned telephones.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell Company engineers made numerous other improvements to the telephone, which emerged as one of the most successful products ever.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1879, the company acquired Edison's patents for the carbon microphone from Western Union.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This made the telephone practical for longer distances, and it was no longer necessary to shout to be heard at the receiving telephone.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pedro II of Brazil was the first person to buy stock in the Bell Telephone Company.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the first telephones in a private residence was installed in his palace in Petrópolis, his summer retreat forty miles (sixty-four kilometres) from Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In January 1915, Bell made the first ceremonial transcontinental telephone call.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Calling from the AT&T head office at 15 Dey Street in New York City, Bell was heard by Thomas Watson at 333 Grant Avenue in San Francisco.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As is sometimes common in scientific discoveries, simultaneous developments occurred, as evidenced by a number of inventors who were at work on the telephone.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Over 18 years, the Bell Telephone Company faced 587 court challenges to its patents, including five that went to the U.S.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Supreme Court, but none was successful in establishing priority over Bell's original patent, and the Bell Telephone Company never lost a case that had proceeded to a final trial stage.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's laboratory notes and family letters were the key to establishing a long lineage to his experiments.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell company lawyers successfully fought off myriad lawsuits generated initially around the challenges by Elisha Gray and Amos Dolbear.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In personal correspondence to Bell, both Gray and Dolbear had acknowledged his prior work, which considerably weakened their later claims.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On January 13, 1887, the U.S. government moved to annul the patent issued to Bell on the grounds of fraud and misrepresentation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After a series of decisions and reversals, the Bell company won a decision in the Supreme Court, though a couple of the original claims from the lower court cases were left undecided.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By the time the trial had wound its way through nine years of legal battles, the U.S. prosecuting attorney had died and the two Bell patents (No.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] 186,787, dated January 30, 1877) were no longer in effect, although the presiding judges agreed to continue the proceedings due to the case's importance as a precedent.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With a change in administration and charges of conflict of interest (on both sides) arising from the original trial, the U.S. attorney general dropped the lawsuit on November 30, 1897, leaving several issues undecided on the merits.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During a deposition filed for the 1887 trial, Italian inventor Antonio Meucci also claimed to have created the first working model of a telephone in Italy in 1834.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1886, in the first of three cases in which he was involved, Meucci took the stand as a witness in hope of establishing his invention's priority.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meucci's testimony was disputed due to lack of material evidence for his inventions, as his working models were purportedly lost at the laboratory of American District Telegraph (ADT) of New York, which was incorporated as a subsidiary of Western Union in 1901.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meucci's work, like that of many other inventors of the period, was based on earlier acoustic principles and, despite evidence of earlier experiments, the final case involving Meucci was eventually dropped upon Meucci's death.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But due to the efforts of Congressman Vito Fossella, on June 11, 2002, the U.S.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] House of Representatives stated that Meucci's "work in the invention of the telephone should be acknowledged".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This did not put an end to the still contentious issue.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Some modern scholars do not agree that Bell's work on the telephone was influenced by Meucci's inventions.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The value of Bell's patent was acknowledged throughout the world, and patent applications were made in most major countries.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell delayed the German patent application, the electrical firm Siemens & Halske set up a rival manufacturer of Bell telephones under its own patent.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Siemens produced near-identical copies of the Bell telephone without having to pay royalties.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The establishment of the International Bell Telephone Company in Brussels, Belgium, in 1880, as well as a series of agreements in other countries eventually consolidated a global telephone operation.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The strain put on Bell by his constant appearances in court, necessitated by the legal battles, eventually resulted in his resignation from the company.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On July 11, 1877, a few days after the Bell Telephone Company was established, Bell married Mabel Hubbard (1857–1923) at the Hubbard estate in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Mabel was the daughter of his patron Gardiner Greene Hubbard (the first president of the National Geographic Society),She was deaf as a result of scarlet fever and was a student of Graham Bell.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His wedding present to his bride was to turn over 1,487 of his 1,497 shares in the newly formed Bell Telephone Company.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Shortly thereafter, the newly-weds embarked on a year-long honeymoon in Europe.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During that excursion, Bell took a handmade model of his telephone with him, making it a "working holiday".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The courtship had begun years earlier; however, Bell waited until he was more financially secure before marrying.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the telephone appeared to be an "instant" success, it was not initially a profitable venture and Bell's main sources of income were from lectures until after 1897.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One unusual request exacted by his fiancée was that he use "Alec" rather than the family's earlier familiar name of "Aleck".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] From 1876, he would sign his name "Alec Bell".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell family home was in Cambridge, Massachusetts, until 1880 when Bell's father-in-law bought a house in Washington, D.C.; in 1882 he bought a home in the same city for Bell's family, so they could be with him while he attended to the numerous court cases involving patent disputes.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was a British subject throughout his early life in Scotland and later in Canada until 1882 when he became a naturalized citizen of the United States.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1915, he characterized his status as: "I am not one of those hyphenated Americans who claim allegiance to two countries." Despite this declaration, Bell has been proudly claimed as a "native son" by all three countries he resided in: the United States, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1885, a new summer retreat was contemplated.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That summer, the Bells had a vacation on Cape Breton Island in Nova Scotia, Canada, spending time at the small village of Baddeck.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning in 1886, Bell started building an estate on a point across from Baddeck, overlooking Bras d'Or Lake.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1889, a large house, christened *The Lodge* was completed and two years later, a larger complex of buildings, including a new laboratory, were begun that the Bells would name Beinn Bhreagh (Gaelic: *Beautiful Mountain*) after Bell's ancestral Scottish Highlands.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell also built the Bell Boatyard on the estate, employing up to 40 people building experimental craft as well as wartime lifeboats and workboats for the Royal Canadian Navy and pleasure craft for the Bell family.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He was an enthusiastic boater, and Bell and his family sailed or rowed a long series of vessels on Bras d'Or Lake, ordering additional vessels from the H.W.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Embree and Sons boatyard in Port Hawkesbury, Nova Scotia.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In his final, and some of his most productive years, Bell split his residency between Washington, D.C., where he and his family initially resided for most of the year, and Beinn Bhreagh, where they spent increasing amounts of time.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Until the end of his life, Bell and his family would alternate between the two homes, but *Beinn Bhreagh* would, over the next 30 years, become more than a summer home as Bell became so absorbed in his experiments that his annual stays lengthened.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Both Mabel and Bell became immersed in the Baddeck community and were accepted by the villagers as "their own".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bells were still in residence at *Beinn Bhreagh* when the Halifax Explosion occurred on December 6, 1917.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Mabel and Bell mobilized the community to help victims in Halifax.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although Alexander Graham Bell is most often associated with the invention of the telephone, his interests were extremely varied.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] According to one of his biographers, Charlotte Gray, Bell's work ranged "unfettered across the scientific landscape" and he often went to bed voraciously reading the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, scouring it for new areas of interest.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The range of Bell's inventive genius is represented only in part by the 18 patents granted in his name alone and the 12 he shared with his collaborators.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These included 14 for the telephone and telegraph, four for the photophone, one for the phonograph, five for aerial vehicles, four for "hydroairplanes", and two for selenium cells.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's inventions spanned a wide range of interests and included a metal jacket to assist in breathing, the audiometer to detect minor hearing problems, a device to locate icebergs, investigations on how to separate salt from seawater, and work on finding alternative fuels.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell worked extensively in medical research and invented techniques for teaching speech to the deaf.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During his Volta Laboratory period, Bell and his associates considered impressing a magnetic field on a record as a means of reproducing sound.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the trio briefly experimented with the concept, they could not develop a workable prototype.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] They abandoned the idea, never realizing they had glimpsed a basic principle which would one day find its application in the tape recorder, the hard disc and floppy disc drive, and other magnetic media.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's own home used a primitive form of air conditioning, in which fans blew currents of air across great blocks of ice.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also anticipated modern concerns with fuel shortages and industrial pollution.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Methane gas, he reasoned, could be produced from the waste of farms and factories.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At his Canadian estate in Nova Scotia, he experimented with composting toilets and devices to capture water from the atmosphere.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In a magazine article published in 1917, he reflected on the possibility of using solar energy to heat houses.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter jointly invented a wireless telephone, named a photophone, which allowed for the transmission of both sounds and normal human conversations on a beam of light.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Both men later became full associates in the Volta Laboratory Association.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On June 21, 1880, Bell's assistant transmitted a wireless voice telephone message a considerable distance, from the roof of the Franklin School in Washington, D.C., to Bell at the window of his laboratory, some 700 feet (213 m) away, 19 years before the first voice radio transmissions.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell believed the photophone's principles were his life's "greatest achievement", telling a reporter shortly before his death that the photophone was "the greatest invention [I have] ever made, greater than the telephone".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The photophone was a precursor to the fiber-optic communication systems which achieved popular worldwide usage in the 1980s.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Its master patent was issued in December 1880, many decades before the photophone's principles came into popular use.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell is also credited with developing one of the early versions of a metal detector through the use of an induction balance, after the shooting of U.S.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] According to some accounts, the metal detector worked flawlessly in tests but did not find Guiteau's bullet, partly because the metal bed frame on which the President was lying disturbed the instrument, resulting in static.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Garfield's surgeons, led by self-appointed chief physician Doctor Willard Bliss, were sceptical of the device, and ignored Bell's requests to move the President to a bed not fitted with metal springs.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Alternatively, although Bell had detected a slight sound on his first test, the bullet may have been lodged too deeply to be detected by the crude apparatus.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's own detailed account, presented to the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1882, differs in several particulars from most of the many and varied versions now in circulation, by concluding that extraneous metal was not to blame for failure to locate the bullet.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Perplexed by the peculiar results he had obtained during an examination of Garfield, Bell "proceeded to the Executive Mansion the next morning ... to ascertain from the surgeons whether they were perfectly sure that all metal had been removed from the neighborhood of the bed.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It was then recollected that underneath the horse-hair mattress on which the President lay was another mattress composed of steel wires.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon obtaining a duplicate, the mattress was found to consist of a sort of net of woven steel wires, with large meshes.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The March 1906 *Scientific American* article by American pioneer William E.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meacham explained the basic principle of hydrofoils and hydroplanes.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell considered the invention of the hydroplane as a very significant achievement.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Based on information gained from that article, he began to sketch concepts of what is now called a hydrofoil boat.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] "Casey" Baldwin began hydrofoil experimentation in the summer of 1908 as a possible aid to airplane takeoff from water.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin studied the work of the Italian inventor Enrico Forlanini and began testing models.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This led him and Bell to the development of practical hydrofoil watercraft.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During his world tour of 1910–11, Bell and Baldwin met with Forlanini in France.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] They had rides in the Forlanini hydrofoil boat over Lake Maggiore.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin described it as being as smooth as flying.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On returning to Baddeck, a number of initial concepts were built as experimental models, including the *Dhonnas Beag* (Scottish Gaelic for 'little devil'), the first self-propelled Bell-Baldwin hydrofoil.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The experimental boats were essentially proof-of-concept prototypes that culminated in the more substantial HD-4, powered by Renault engines.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] A top speed of 54 miles per hour (87 km/h) was achieved, with the hydrofoil exhibiting rapid acceleration, good stability, and steering, along with the ability to take waves without difficulty.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell hired Walter Pinaud, a Sydney yacht designer and builder as well as the proprietor of Pinaud's Yacht Yard in Westmount, Nova Scotia, to work on the pontoons of the HD-4.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pinaud soon took over the boatyard at Bell Laboratories on Beinn Bhreagh, Bell's estate near Baddeck, Nova Scotia.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pinaud's experience in boatbuilding enabled him to make useful design changes to the HD-4.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After the First World War, work began again on the HD-4.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Navy permitted him to obtain two 350-horsepower (260-kilowatt) engines in July 1919.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On September 9, 1919, the HD-4 set a world marine speed record of 70.86 miles per hour (114.04 kilometres per hour), a record which stood for one year.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1891, Bell had begun experiments to develop motor-powered heavier-than-air aircraft.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA was first formed as Bell shared the vision to fly with his wife, who advised him to seek "young" help as Bell was at the age of 60.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1898, Bell experimented with tetrahedral box kites and wings constructed of multiple compound tetrahedral kites covered in maroon silk.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The tetrahedral wings were named *Cygnet* I, II, and III, and were flown both unmanned and manned (*Cygnet I* crashed during a flight carrying Selfridge) in the period from 1907 to 1912.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Some of Bell's kites are on display at the Alexander Graham Bell National Historic Site.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was a supporter of aerospace engineering research through the Aerial Experiment Association (AEA), officially formed at Baddeck, Nova Scotia, in October 1907 at the suggestion of his wife Mabel and with her financial support after the sale of some of her real estate.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA was headed by Bell and the founding members were four young men: American Glenn H.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Federal government and one of the few people in the army who believed that aviation was the future; Frederick W.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin, the first Canadian and first British subject to pilot a public flight in Hammondsport, New York; and J.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] McCurdy–Baldwin and McCurdy being new engineering graduates from the University of Toronto.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA's work progressed to heavier-than-air machines, applying their knowledge of kites to gliders.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Moving to Hammondsport, the group then designed and built the *Red Wing*, framed in bamboo and covered in red silk and powered by a small air-cooled engine.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 12, 1908, over Keuka Lake, the biplane lifted off on the first public flight in North America.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The innovations that were incorporated into this design included a cockpit enclosure and tail rudder (later variations on the original design would add ailerons as a means of control).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the AEA's inventions, a practical wingtip form of the aileron, was to become a standard component on all aircraft.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The *White Wing* and *June Bug* were to follow and by the end of 1908, over 150 flights without mishap had been accomplished.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] However, the AEA had depleted its initial reserves and only a $15,000 grant from Mrs.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell allowed it to continue with experiments.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Selfridge had also become the first person killed in a powered heavier-than-air flight in a crash of the Wright Flyer at Fort Myer, Virginia, on September 17, 1908.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Their final aircraft design, the *Silver Dart*, embodied all of the advancements found in the earlier machines.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On February 23, 1909, Bell was present as the *Silver Dart* flown by J.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] McCurdy from the frozen ice of Bras d'Or made the first aircraft flight in Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell had worried that the flight was too dangerous and had arranged for a doctor to be on hand.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With the successful flight, the AEA disbanded and the *Silver Dart* would revert to Baldwin and McCurdy, who began the Canadian Aerodrome Company and would later demonstrate the aircraft to the Canadian Army.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell, along with many members of the scientific community at the time, took an interest in the popular science of heredity which grew out of the publication of Charles Darwin's book *On the Origin of Species* in 1859.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] On his estate in Nova Scotia, Bell conducted meticulously recorded breeding experiments with rams and ewes.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Over the course of more than 30 years, Bell sought to produce a breed of sheep with multiple nipples that would bear twins.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He specifically wanted to see if selective breeding could produce sheep with four functional nipples with enough milk for twin lambs.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] This interest in animal breeding caught the attention of scientists focused on the study of heredity and genetics in humans.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In November 1883, Bell presented a paper at a meeting of the National Academy of Sciences titled *Upon the Formation of a Deaf Variety of the Human Race*.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The paper is a compilation of data on the hereditary aspects of deafness.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's research indicated that a hereditary tendency toward deafness, as indicated by the possession of deaf relatives, was an important element in determining the production of deaf offspring.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He noted that the proportion of deaf children born to deaf parents was many times greater than the proportion of deaf children born to the general population.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In the paper, Bell delved into social commentary and discussed hypothetical public policies to bring an end to deafness.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He also criticized educational practices that segregated deaf children rather than integrating them fully into mainstream classrooms.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A review of Bell's *Memoir upon the Formation of a Deaf Variety of the Human Race* appearing in an 1885 issue of the *American Annals of the Deaf and Dumb* states that "Dr.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Historians have noted that Bell explicitly opposed laws regulating marriage, and never mentioned sterilization in any of his writings.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Even after Bell agreed to engage with scientists conducting eugenic research, he consistently refused to support public policy that limited the rights or privileges of the deaf.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's interest and research on heredity attracted the interest of Charles Davenport, a Harvard professor and head of the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1906, Davenport, who was also the founder of the American Breeder's Association, approached Bell about joining a new committee on eugenics chaired by David Starr Jordan.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1910, Davenport opened the Eugenics Records office at Cold Spring Harbor.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] To give the organization scientific credibility, Davenport set up a Board of Scientific Directors naming Bell as chairman.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Other members of the board included Luther Burbank, Roswell H.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1921, a Second International Congress of Eugenics was held in New York at the Museum of Natural History and chaired by Davenport.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Although Bell did not present any research or speak as part of the proceedings, he was named as honorary president as a means to attract other scientists to attend the event.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A summary of the event notes that Bell was a "pioneering investigator in the field of human heredity".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell died of complications arising from diabetes on August 2, 1922, at his private estate in Cape Breton, Nova Scotia, at age 75.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell had also been affected by pernicious anemia.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] His last view of the land he had inhabited was by moonlight on his mountain estate at 2:00 a.m.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] While tending to him after his long illness, Mabel, his wife, whispered, "Don't leave me." By way of reply, Bell signed "no...", lost consciousness, and died shortly after.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] On learning of Bell's death, the Canadian Prime Minister, Mackenzie King, cabled Mrs.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's coffin was constructed of Beinn Bhreagh pine by his laboratory staff, lined with the same red silk fabric used in his tetrahedral kite experiments.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Upon the conclusion of Bell's funeral, for one minute at 6:25 p.m.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Eastern Time, "every phone on the continent of North America was silenced in honor of the man who had given to mankind the means for direct communication at a distance".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Alexander Graham Bell was buried atop Beinn Bhreagh mountain, on his estate where he had resided increasingly for the last 35 years of his life, overlooking Bras d'Or Lake.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He was survived by his wife Mabel, his two daughters, Elsie May and Marian, and nine of his grandchildren.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Honours and tributes flowed to Bell in increasing numbers as his invention became ubiquitous and his personal fame grew.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell received numerous honorary degrees from colleges and universities to the point that the requests almost became burdensome.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] During his life, he also received dozens of major awards, medals, and other tributes.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] These included statuary monuments to both him and the new form of communication his telephone created, including the Bell Telephone Memorial erected in his honour in *Alexander Graham Bell Gardens* in Brantford, Ontario, in 1917.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A number of historic sites and other marks commemorate Bell in North America and Europe, including the first telephone companies in the United States and Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1880, Bell received the Volta Prize with a purse of 50,000 French francs (approximately US$350,000 in today's currency) for the invention of the telephone from the French government.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Among the luminaries who judged were Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Volta Prize was conceived by Napoleon III in 1852, and named in honour of Alessandro Volta, with Bell becoming the second recipient of the grand prize in its history.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Volta Laboratory became an experimental facility devoted to scientific discovery, and the very next year it improved Edison's phonograph by substituting wax for tinfoil as the recording medium and incising the recording rather than indenting it, key upgrades that Edison himself later adopted.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In partnership with Gardiner Greene Hubbard, Bell helped establish the publication *Science* during the early 1880s.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1898, Bell was elected as the second president of the National Geographic Society, serving until 1903, and was primarily responsible for the extensive use of illustrations, including photography, in the magazine.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He also served for many years as a Regent of the Smithsonian Institution (1898–1922).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He was one of the founders of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers in 1884 and served as its president from 1891 to 1892.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell was later awarded the AIEE's Edison Medal in 1914 "For meritorious achievement in the invention of the telephone".
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The *bel* (B) and the smaller *decibel* (dB) are units of measurement of sound pressure level (SPL) invented by Bell Labs and named after him.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Since 1976, the IEEE's Alexander Graham Bell Medal has been awarded to honour outstanding contributions in the field of telecommunications.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1936, the US Patent Office declared Bell first on its list of the country's greatest inventors, leading to the US Post Office issuing a commemorative stamp honouring Bell in 1940 as part of its 'Famous Americans Series'.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The First Day of Issue ceremony was held on October 28 in Boston, Massachusetts, the city where Bell spent considerable time on research and working with the deaf.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Bell stamp became very popular and sold out in little time.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The stamp became, and remains to this day, the most valuable one of the series.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The 150th anniversary of Bell's birth in 1997 was marked by a special issue of commemorative £1 banknotes from the Royal Bank of Scotland.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Additionally, the Government of Canada honoured Bell in 1997 with a C$100 gold coin, in tribute also to the 150th anniversary of his birth, and with a silver dollar coin in 2009 in honour of the 100th anniversary of flight in Canada.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] That first flight was made by an airplane designed under Dr.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's image, and also those of his many inventions have graced paper money, coinage, and postal stamps in numerous countries worldwide for many dozens of years.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Alexander Graham Bell was ranked 57th among the 100 Greatest Britons (2002) in an official BBC nationwide poll, and among the Top Ten Greatest Canadians (2004), and the 100 Greatest Americans (2005).
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 2006, Bell was also named as one of the 10 greatest Scottish scientists in history after having been listed in the National Library of Scotland's 'Scottish Science Hall of Fame'.
[src:alexander-graham-bell/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's name is still widely known and used as part of the names of dozens of educational institutes, corporate namesakes, street and place names around the world.
